content.problemStatement:
- External CSS is the industry standard for styling websites. Instead of keeping your styles inside the HTML file, you create a separate file (like `styles.css`) to hold all your design rules.

This method is the best practice because:  
- **One File, Many Pages:** A single CSS file can style your entire website.  
- **Easy to Update:** Change one line in your `styles.css` file, and the changes apply instantly to every page you've linked it to.  
- **Clean Code:** It keeps your HTML file focused on structure and content, while your CSS file handles all the visuals.
---
You link your HTML file to your CSS file using the `` tag inside the `` section. The `href` attribute points to your CSS file's location.
